exposure (Riddle et al., 2003). However, later there were reports of
an elevation in risk for hospitalization due to circulatory diseases
(Smith et al., 2003) and a two-fold increase in the incidence of brain
cancer deaths (Bullman et al., 2005).
After the Persian Gulf War ended, the Department of Defense
(DoD) and the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) initiated efforts to
determine the extent of potential human GB/GF exposure by
modeling its estimated release from and dispersion around the
Khamisiyah site (Persian Gulf War Illness Task Force, 1997). Using
available meteorological data and estimates of atmospheric
transport and diffusion, this ‘‘plume’’ analysis resulted in four
modeled hazard areas, one corresponding to each of 4 days (10–13

