Decrements in manual dexterity and visuospatial function
(Proctor et al., 2006) and reduced total brain white matter (WM)
volume (Heaton et al., 2007) have been noted 4–6 years after
exposure in GW veterans with higher estimated levels of
presumed GB/GF exposure. Recently, we reported reduced total
gray matter (GM) and hippocampal volumes in a different cohort
of 40 GW veterans with suspected GB/GF exposure more than a
decade after exposure (Chao et al., 2010). Based on these ﬁndings
and the results of Heaton et al., we argued that there was a
compelling reason to conduct a follow-up study with more
subjects and more sophisticated imaging technology. Therefore,
the goal of this study is to replicate and extend our previous
ﬁndings in a different cohort of GW veterans with suspected GB/
GF exposure. We used a 4 T MRI scanner, which affords better
signal-to-noise ratio, reduced voxel size, and improved GM/WM
contrast than the 1.5 T scanner that we and Heaton used in our
previous studies.
2. Methods
2.1. Description of exposure and exposure dosage estimates
The Department of Defense and the Central Intelligence Agency
initiated efforts to determine the extent of potential human GB/GF
exposure by modeling its estimated release from and dispersion
around the Khamisiyah site (Persian Gulf War Illness Task Force,
1997). The possible hazard areas, which were estimated using
available meteorological data and estimates of atmospheric
transport and diffusion, were determined by the Ofﬁce of the
Special Assistant for Gulf War Illnesses (OSAGWI), with assistance
from the Naval Research Laboratory, Naval Surface Warfare Center,
the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, and the Defense
Threat Reduction Agency. This ‘‘plume’’ analysis resulted in four
modeled hazard areas, one corresponding to each of 4 days (10–13
March 1991) when GB/GF release was considered to be possible.
Each model contained the area within the concentration contour of
the general population limit (GPL), which reﬂects the limit below
which individuals within the general population could be exposed
24 h per day for 70 years without experiencing any adverse health
effects. The US army and the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention estimate the GPL value to be 0.01296 mg min/m3
(McNamara and Leitnaker, 1971). The plume estimates were then
superimposed onto geographic maps containing military unit
locations. A soldier was considered potentially exposed to low
levels of GB/GF if his or her unit had been located within the
modeled hazard area on any of the four target dates. In 2002, the
exposure plume models were reanalyzed and revised using
updated troop location and personnel information, improved
meteorological modeling, more accurate estimates of the total
number of GB/GF-containing rockets destroyed, consideration of
the methods used to remove GB/GF from the area, relevant
exposure thresholds for GB/GF, and the combined toxicity of these
agents.
We requested and received information about exposure status
and the cumulative exposure level estimates for all of the GW
veterans who participated in our studies on the effects of Gulf
War Illness from the Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense for
Force Health Protection and Readiness. The exposure level
estimates reﬂect the cumulative exposure level estimate for the
unit to which each study participant was assigned from 10 to

