13 March 1991. Because the last modeling effort that determined
the exposure estimates occurred in 2002, individuals who were
not identiﬁed in initial data collections but were later identiﬁed as
having been with units that were in the hazard area, do not have
cumulative exposure level estimates. In the current sample, 13%
(N = 8) of the participants who had been potentially exposed
to GB/GF exposure did not have cumulative exposure level
estimates.
2.2. Participants
All participants were veterans of the 1991 Persian Gulf War
who took part in our 4 T imaging studies on the effects of Gulf War
Illness on the brain, conducted at the San Francisco Veterans Affairs
Medical Center between 2005 and 2010. Information obtained
from the ofﬁce of the Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense for
Force Health Protection and Readiness, which maintains the
database of individuals who are considered to have been in the
possible hazard areas, identiﬁed 77 GW veterans from the sample
of 213 as having potentially been exposed to GB/GF according to
the revised plume modeling data. Because our goal was to replicate
our previous ﬁndings in a different cohort of GB/GF exposed
veterans, data from 8 veterans who had also participated in our
1.5-T study of Gulf War Illness were excluded from the current
analysis. Five veterans with suspected GB/GF exposure did not
have imaging data due to claustrophobia. Thus, we had 4 T imaging
data from 64 GW veterans with suspected GB/GF exposure. Of the
remaining 136 unexposed GW veterans, we matched 64 veterans
to our cohort of exposed veterans based age, sex, level of education,
Chronic Multisymptom Illness (CMI, Fukuda et al., 1998), current
posttraumatic stress disorder (PTSD) and current major depressive
disorder (MDD) status. The Institutional Review Boards of the
University of California San Francisco and San Francisco VA and the
DoD Human Research Protection Ofﬁce approved both studies.
Informed consent was obtained from all participants.
2.3. Study protocol and measures
The complete study protocol included 9 self-report questionnaires about physical and mental health status, a battery of
neuropsychological tests, a psychological diagnostic interview, a
medical examination, and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) on a
4-T scanner. For the majority of participants, neuropsychological
testing and MRI scans took place on the same day. In a few cases,
neuropsychological testing and MRI scans were administered 1
day apart.
2.4. Neuropsychological battery and clinical assessment
We used the Continuous Performance Test (CPT, Letz, 1991), the
Digit Span forward subtest of the Wechsler Adult Intelligence
Scale-III (WAIS-III; Wechsler, 1997), and the Trail-Making Test,
Part A (TMT A, Reitan and Wolfson, 1985) to assess simple
attention. Executive function was assessed with the Trail-Making
Test, Part B (TMT B, Reitan and Wolfson, 1985), the Short Category
Test, Wetzel and Boll, 1987), and the Digit Span backward subtest
of the WAIS-III. We used the California Verbal Learning Test-II
(CVLT, Delis et al., 2000) to assess memory, focusing on raw scores
for the short- and long-delay free recall and recognition memory
test. Manual dexterity was assessed with the Grooved Pegboard
test (Lafayette Instrument, Lafayette, IN). The Test of Memory
Malingering (TOMM; Tombaugh, 1995) was used to assess
tendency to purposefully perform poorly. A TOMM score <90%
(i.e., <45/50 correct) on trial 2 and/or the retention trial was
operationalized as failing the TOMM. The clinical diagnoses of
current MDD and current PTSD were made based on the Structured

