2.5. Magnetic resonance imaging
A volumetric T1-weighted gradient echo MRI (MPRAGE; TR/TE/
TI = 2300/3/950 ms, 1.0 mm  1.0 mm  1.0 mm resolution) was
acquired on a Bruker MedSpec 4 T system equipped with a USA
instruments eight-channel array head coil.
2.5.1. Tissue segmentation
We used SPM8 (Statistical Parametric Mapping; Institute of
Neurology, London, United Kingdom) to segment the volumetric
T1 images into gray matter (GM), white matter (WM) and cerebral
spinal ﬂuid (CSF) with the default uniﬁed segmentation algorithm.
In order to calculate the volumes of the separate tissue
compartments, we determined the number of voxels belonging
to the GM, WM or CSF partitions. Each volume count was then
multiplied with the voxel dimensions (1 mm  1 mm  1 mm)
and converted into cubic centimeters. Every single voxel in the
compartmental images contains a certain probability value,
ranging from zero to one, identifying the likelihood that this
voxel belongs to a particular compartment. Hence we also
multiplied the number of voxels with the probability values of
each voxel. After determining volumes of the GM, WM and CSF
compartments, total intracranial volume (ICV) was calculated by
summing the compartmental volumes (i.e., GM + WM + CSF).
We also performed a voxel-based morphometry (VBM) analysis
using SPM8 and MATLAB R2008a (Math-Works, Natick, MA, USA).
First, MR images were segmented into GM, WM and cerebrospinal
ﬂuid (CSF) using the standard uniﬁed segmentation model in SPM8
(Ashburner and Friston, 2005). Second, GM and WM population
templates were generated from the entire image dataset using the
diffeomorphic anatomical registration using exponentiated Lie
algebra (DARTEL) technique (Ashburner, 2007). Third, after an
initial afﬁne registration of the GM and WM DARTEL templates to
the tissue probability maps in Montreal Neurological Institute
(MNI) space (http://www.mni.mcgill.ca/), non-linear warping of
GM and WM images were performed to the DARTEL GM and WM
templates in MNI space. Fourth, images were then modulated to
ensure that relative volumes of GM and WM were preserved
following the spatial normalization procedure. Lastly, images were
smoothed with an 8 mm full width at half maximum Gaussian
kernel. After spatial pre-processing, the smoothed, modulated,
normalized GM and WM datasets were used for statistical analysis.
2.6. Statistical analyses
Statistical analyses of the demographic, clinical, neuropsychological, and volumetric measures were conducted using IBM SPSS
Statistics, version 19. Demographic and descriptive characteristics
were compared across the two dichotomous exposure groups with
Student’s t-tests for continuous variables and chi-square tests for
categorical variables. Analyses of the neuropsychological and
volumetric imaging data were carried out in three stages. First,
binary comparisons of the 64 exposed GW veterans and the 64
matched, unexposed GW veterans were performed with Student’s ttests. Next, we used linear regression analyses to examine the
impact of potential confounding factors (e.g., PTSD and depression
symptoms, history of alcohol abuse/dependence, and current
average number of drinks/month). These variables were forced into
the regression equation in the ﬁrst step. CMI and GB/GF exposure
status were forced into the regression equation in the second and
third steps respectively, to determine their ability to predict
neuropsychological performance and brain volume over demo-

graphic, clinical, and psychosocial variables. Thirdly, we used
hierarchical linear regression analyses to determine if a dose–
response relationship existed between cumulative levels of
estimated GB/GF exposure and brain volume and neuropsychological performance in the exposed GW veterans. In these analyses, age,
gender, ICV (for analyses of brain volume data), education (for
analyses of the neuropsychological data), symptoms of PTSD and
depression, history of alcohol abuse/dependence, current drinking
level, CMI status, and cumulative exposure level estimates were
entered as independent predictors of brain volume and neuropsychological test scores in chronological order. Finally, we used
Spearman’s rank correlations to assess the relationship between
neuropsychological performance and brain volume (i.e., total gray
and white matter), separately in the exposed and unexposed groups.
For the VBM analyses, between group regional differences in
GM and WM volumes were assessed using the general linear model
in SPM8, and the signiﬁcance of each effect was estimated from the
distributional approximations of Gaussian random ﬁelds (Friston
et al., 1994). An absolute threshold mask of 0.05 was used for the
GM and WM analyses. Age, gender and ICV were entered into the
design matrix as nuisance covariates. Signiﬁcant effects were
assessed using the family-wise error (FWE) threshold of
PFWE  0.05, corrected for multiple comparisons.
3. Results
Table 1 summarizes the demographic, military, and clinical data
of the 64 GB/GF exposed GW veterans who had imaging data and
the 64 unexposed, matched controls. The two groups were
matched for age, gender, years of education, and diagnoses of
current PTSD, current MDD, and CMI based on criteria previously
described by Fukuda et al. (1998). However, there were group
differences in ethnicity (x2 = 11.0, p = 0.03) and years of military
service (p = 0.04).
3.1. Binary comparisons of the Neuropsychological and 4 T MRI data
in the exposed and unexposed GW veterans
Table 2 lists the neuropsychological and volumetric MRI data
of the 64 GB/GF exposed subjects and the matched controls. The
GB/GF exposed subjects performed more quickly than the
unexposed subjects on the TMT-A (p < 0.001) and Grooved
Pegboard with the non-dominant hand (p < 0.05). Importantly,
there was no difference in the number of ambidextrous subjects
in exposed and unexposed groups (3% vs. 4% respectively,
p > 0.8). On the CPT test, GB/GF exposed subjects made more
errors of omission (p = 0.02) and tended to have slower response
times (p = 0.05) than unexposed subjects. Analysis of the SPM8
segmentation data revealed reduced total GM and WM volume
(p = 0.03) in the GB/GF exposed subjects compared to the
matched controls. Nothing from the VBM analyses of the GM
or WM segmentation maps survived FWE corrections for
multiple comparisons.
3.2. Consideration of potential confounding variables
Table 3 summarizes the results of the multiple linear regression
analyses that examined the ability of GB/GF exposure status to
predict GM and WM volumes and neuropsychological performance over and above potential confounding variables. Consistent
with results from the binary comparisons, GB/GF exposure status
was a signiﬁcant predictor of GM (b = 0.11, p = 0.02) and WM
(b = 0.14, p = 0.03) volumes, performance on the TMT-A
(b = 0.32, p < 0.001), Grooved Pegboard, non-dominant hand
(b = 0.19, p = 0.03), and number of CPT omission errors (b = 0.22,
