Because the regression analyses also revealed CMI status,
entered in the second step, to be a signiﬁcant predictor of total WM
volume (b = 0.17, p < 0.05), we further examined the relationship between CMI status and WM volume in a post hoc analysis.
Because the regression model showed that gender, history of
alcohol abuse/dependence, and current drinking level were not
signiﬁcantly associated with total WM volume, these variables
were excluded from the post hoc analysis of covariance (ANCOVA).
The ANCOVA, which controlled for age, ICV, current CAPS and
HAMD scores, revealed a marginal effect of CMI status (p = 0.06) on
total brain WM volume.
The regression analyses also revealed a signiﬁcant relationship
between CMI status and CPT errors of commission (b = 0.29,
p = 0.01). Because none of the independent variables were
signiﬁcantly associated with CPT commission errors, they were
not included in the post hoc one-way analysis of variance
(ANOVA) that we used to further examine the relationship
between CMI status and CPT commission errors. This post hoc
analysis revealed a signiﬁcant main effect of CMI on commission
errors (F1,107 = 25.35, p < 0.001). Subjects with CMI committed
more commission errors (14.1  6.0) on the CPT than subjects
without CMI- (8.6  5.2 errors). CMI status was also signiﬁcantly
associated with performance on the Grooved Pegboard with the nondominant hand (b = 0.23, p < 0.03). Of all the independent
variables in the regression analysis, only age and exposure status
were signiﬁcantly associated with Grooved Pegboard performance.
Thus, we examined the relationship between CMI status and
Grooved Pegboard performance in a post hoc ANCOVA that
controlled for age and GB/GF exposure. This analysis revealed only
a marginal effect of CMI status (F1,126 = 3.19, p = 0.08) on Grooved
Pegboard performance with the non-dominant hand.

