3.3. Examination of dose–response relationship between estimated
levels of GB/GF exposure and brain volume and neuropsychological
performance
Table 4 summarizes the results of the hierarchical regression
analyses used to examine the relationship between estimated
levels of GB/GF exposure and brain volume. Cumulative exposure
level estimates did not signiﬁcantly predict GM or WM volume. In
contrast, ICV and CMI status signiﬁcantly predicted both. Age was
also a signiﬁcant predictor of total brain GM volume while
current CAPS score and current drinking level predicted total
brain WM volume. Table 5 summarizes a similar analysis of the
relationship between cumulative exposure level estimates and
neuropsychological performance. Age (b = 0.31, p = 0.06) and
CMI status (b = 0.40, p = 0.01) were both signiﬁcant be
predictors of the number of CPT commission errors in the GB/
GF exposed veterans.
3.4. Interaction between GB/GF exposure and CMI status on
brain volume
The ﬁnding that CMI status signiﬁcantly predicted GM and WM
volume in the regression analyses of 56 exposed veterans, and
signiﬁcantly predicted WM volume in the regression model that
we used to examine potentially confounding variables prompted
us to further investigate the relationship between CMI and GB/GF
exposure status on brain volume. We initially used a one-way
ANCOVA that controlled for ICV, age, gender, and psychosocial
variables (i.e., current CAPS and HAMD scores, history of alcohol
abuse/dependence and current drinking levels) separately in the
exposed and unexposed veterans. This analysis revealed a
signiﬁcant main effect of CMI status on GM (F1,63 = 12.29,
p = 0.001) and WM (F1,63 = 7.39, p = 0.009) volume in the GB/GF
exposed veterans, with smaller volumes in veterans with CMI. In

contrast, there was no effect of CMI on GM (F1,63 = 1.36, p = 0.25) or
WM (F1,63 = 0.87, p = 0.36) volumes in the unexposed veterans.
Next, we used a 2-way ANCOVA, with GB/GF exposure and CMI
status as between-subject factors, to investigate the interaction
between CMI and GB/GF exposure status. As expected, there were
signiﬁcant effects of GB/GF exposure on both GM (F1,127 = 5.52,
p = 0.02) and WM (F1,127 = 4.82, p = 0.03) volume. There was also a
signiﬁcant effect of CMI status on GM volume (F1,127 = 3.94,
p = 0.049). However, CMI and GB/GF exposure status only
interacted signiﬁcant for GM volume (F1,127 = 6.17, p = 0.01) and
not for WM volume (F1,127 = 0.07, p = 0.80).
3.5. Relationship between brain volume and neuropsychological
performance
Table 6 lists the Spearman’s correlation coefﬁcients between
total GM and WM volumes and neuropsychological test scores. In
the exposed veterans, total GM volume correlated positively with
short- (r = 0.39, p = 0.002) and long- (r = 0.31, p = 0.01) delay free
recall on the CVLT, and Digit Span, backwards on the WAIS-III
(r = 0.25, p = 0.047). Total WM volume also correlated positively
with short-delay free recall on the CVLT (r = 0.30, p = 0.02). In
contrast, there were no signiﬁcant correlations between brain
volume and neuropsychological test performance in the group of
64 unexposed veterans.
