In 1994 the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention used
factor analysis to deﬁne a symptom complex termed ‘‘chronic
multisymptom illness’’ (CMI). CMI was deﬁned as the presence, for
6 months or longer, of one or more symptoms from at least two of
the following clusters: general fatigue, mood and cognitive
abnormalities, and musculoskeletal pain (Fukuda et al., 1998).
Shortly after the 1991 Gulf War, CMI was noted to be quite
common in all GW veterans but more prevalent in deployed than in
nondeployed veterans (Steele, 2000; Unwin et al., 1999; Wolfe
et al., 2002). Several studies have reported spectroscopic abnormalities in the brains of ill GW veterans (e.g., Haley et al., 2000;
Menon et al., 2004). However, to our knowledge, this is the ﬁrst
report of an interaction between Gulf War Illness/CMI and GB/GF
exposure on brain volume. Results of the post hoc 2-way ANCOVA
in the entire sample of 128 GW veterans suggest that the
interaction is stronger for GM than WM volume.
Linear regression and a one-way ANOVA also showed Gulf War
Illness/CMI status to be signiﬁcantly associated increased numbers
of commission errors on the CPT. The results of studies
investigating cognitive dysfunction associated with Gulf War
Illness/CMI have been mixed. Many studies have shown signiﬁcant
deﬁcits in cognitive performance in samples of ill GW veterans
(Binder et al., 2001; Haley et al., 1997; Hom et al., 1997; Lange
et al., 2001; Storzbach et al., 2001; Sullivan et al., 2003 147).
However, some of these differences were only observed when
subgroups were analyzed (Anger et al., 1999; White et al., 2001).
Moreover, two studies have failed to ﬁnd any signiﬁcant
neuropsychological test differences between ill and healthy GW
veterans (Goldstein et al., 1996; Vasterling et al., 2003). In the
current study, when we used hierarchical regression analyses to
examine possible dose–response relationships between estimated
levels of exposure and neuropsychological performance in the
exposed subjects, CMI status was not a signiﬁcant predictor of CPT
commission errors. Therefore, we need to be cautious about
inferring any potential relationship between CMI status and
performance on the CPT.
Consistent with our previous study, we did not ﬁnd evidence of
a dose–response relationship between cumulative exposure
estimates and GM or WM volumes in the present study. Although
hierarchical regression analysis showed cumulative exposure
estimate to be a signiﬁcant predictor of number of CPT commission
errors, the negative standardized regression coefﬁcient (b = 0.40)
suggests that veterans with higher exposure level estimates
committed fewer commission errors than veterans with lower
exposure level estimates. Upon careful review of the data, we
found that six veterans with the highest exposure level estimates
(0.83–1.05 mg min/m3) who committed only a moderate number
of commission errors on the CPT (4–16). When these six veterans

were excluded from the regression analysis, exposure level
estimates no longer predicted number of CPT commission errors.
Thus, there is likely no relationship between cumulative exposure
estimates and performance on the CPT.
Although GB/GF exposure was not associated with deﬁcits on
neurobehavioral measures of memory or manual dexterity in the
current study, binary analyses of the neuropsychological data did
show that GB/GF exposed veterans responded more quickly than
unexposed veterans on the TMT A and Grooved Pegboard with the
non-dominant hand. Regression analyses conﬁrmed that even
after accounting for demographic, clinical, and psychosocial
variables, GB/GF exposure status still signiﬁcantly predicted
TMT A and Grooved Pegboard performance with the non-dominant
hand. The negative standardized regression coefﬁcients (b = 0.32
for TMT A and b = 0.18 for Grooved Pegboard) indicate that the
exposed veterans had shorter response times than unexposed
veterans. Proctor et al. (2006) similarly found better Finger
Tapping performance among GW veterans with higher than lower
estimated GB/GF exposures and they speculated that it might
relate to the occupational training and skill set abilities of military
personnel more likely to be in the higher exposure areas. Although
this explanation could also account for the faster response times
that we observed on TMT A and Grooved Pegboard with the nondominant hand in the exposed veterans, it is noteworthy that we
did not ﬁnd any signiﬁcant group differences on TMT B or Grooved
Pegboard performance with the dominant hand. Moreover, we did
not ﬁnd an effect of GB/GF exposure on these measures in our
previous study. Thus, it may be possible that the current ﬁndings of
faster response times on these two neuropsychological measures
in exposed GW veterans are spurious results.
Although there were no effects of GB/GF exposure on the CVLT
or Digit Span measures that we examined, there were positive
correlations between GM and WM volume CVLT short and long
delay free recall and the backwards Digit Span in GB/GF exposed
veterans. These correlations suggest that the reduced GM and WM
volume that we observed in GB/GF exposed veterans had some
deleterious effect on memory and executive function abilities.
This study has some limitations: (1) We did not have
information about the veteran’s unit or whether the veterans
were ofﬁcers or enlisted personnel during the Persian Gulf War. (2)
We did not have information about severity of the symptoms
associated with CMI, smoking status, or history of head injury;
although history of head injury associated with prolonged loss of
consciousness was exclusionary for the study. (3) The cumulative
GB/GF exposure level estimates were calculated at the unit rather
than individual level. Therefore, there is no deﬁnitive way of
checking if an individual soldier was with his or her unit on the four
target dates the model. Moreover, the modeled exposure estimates
may be subject to misclassiﬁcation (United States General
Accounting Ofﬁce, 2004). However, general misclassiﬁcation
errors are likely to be random, thus would have limited inﬂuence
on the present results. These limitations notwithstanding, the
current ﬁndings replicate a previous report by our group of
reduced gray-matter volume in GW veterans with suspected
exposure to low levels of GB/GF. These ﬁndings also conﬁrm the
ﬁndings of white matter changes in GW veterans with suspected
exposure to low levels of GB/GF by Heaton et al. (2007). Moreover,
there we found some evidence of an interaction between GB/GF
exposure and CMI status on total GM volume.
Although the long term consequences of GB/GF exposure are
not known, it is recognized that brain injury due to head trauma
(Corkin et al., 1989; Himanen et al., 2006; Klein et al., 1996) or
cerebrovascular disease and stroke (Kokmen et al., 1996; Luchsinger et al., 2005; Mielke et al., 2007; Tatemichi et al., 1994) are
associated with increased risk for cognitive decline and dementia
due to Alzheimer’s disease. Neurotoxin exposure has also been

L.L. Chao et al. / NeuroToxicology 32 (2011) 814–822

implicated as a possible causative factor in the development of
Parkinson’s disease (Liou et al., 1997; Seidler et al., 1996; Semchuk
et al., 1992). Furthermore, a number of reports suggest that
reduced brain ‘‘reserve’’ is also a risk factor in the development of
Alzheimer’s disease (Satz, 1993; Stern, 2006). Taken together,
these ﬁndings argue for further investigation of the long-term
effects of GB/GB exposure and CMI/Gulf War Illness in GW
veterans, including replication of the current ﬁndings in an
epidemiologically sampled cohort studied at multiple sites across
the United States. The fact that nearly 100,000 troops were
potentially exposed to sublethal levels of GB/GF during the Persian
Gulf War emphasizes the importance of these results, and the need
to investigate further their possible consequences on aging and
veteran health.
